<HL>
   Who's News:
   Cooperman, Thoman
   Named to Head Unit
   Of American Express
</HL>
<DATE>
09/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- American Express Co. named two executives to
head its largest and most profitable unit, American Express
Travel Related Services Co.
   Edwin M. Cooperman and G. Richard Thoman were named
chairmen and co-chief executive officers of the charge card,
traveler's check, and travel business, effective Jan. 1. They
will succeed Aldo Papone. Mr. Papone, 58 years old, began
cutting back on his activities for medical reasons in April
1989, when he was named chairman. He will become senior
adviser to American Express, reporting to Chairman James D.
Robinson III, and will continue as a director of the parent.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Cooperman, 46, has been president TRS North America
since 1989, responsible for businesses in the U.S. and
Canada. Mr. Thoman, also 46, was named president of American
Express International in 1989, responsible for American
Express activities outside North America.
   In 1989, the travel-related services unit had profit of
$830 million on revenue of $8.4 billion.
</TEXT>
